  "insights": {
    "title": "Insights on Current Use of Traditional Contraception Methods Among All Women",
    "subtitle": "AI-generated insights based on National Demographic and Health Survey data on modern contraceptive use",
    "overview": "Traditional contraceptive use among all women aged 15 to 49 declined nationally from 9.8 percent in 2022 to 8.1 percent in 2025. The decline appears in most background groups, but levels still vary widely by age, parity, and region.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "National level moved down, with withdrawal still dominant",
        "body": "At the national level, any traditional method fell from 9.8 percent in 2022 to 8.1 percent in 2025. Withdrawal remains the main component (8.1 to 6.8), while calendar/rhythm is smaller (1.7 to 1.3). Other traditional methods stayed near zero in both years."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Use remains concentrated in older ages",
        "body": "Traditional-method use is very low at ages 15-19 (0.6 in 2025), then rises steadily through adulthood and peaks at 35-39 and 40-44 (both 12.7), before easing at 45-49 (10.0). Every age group shows a lower level in 2025 than in 2022."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Women with children still report higher traditional use",
        "body": "In 2025, women with no children reported 1.8 percent, while women with 1-2 children reported 14.7 percent. Use remains elevated for women with 3-4 children (11.0) and 5+ children (10.9). This profile is similar to 2022, but at lower levels overall."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Regional spread is substantial",
        "body": "In 2025, regional levels ranged from 3.2 percent in BARMM to 12.1 percent in Eastern Visayas. Other high regions were Ilocos Region (11.8), Western Visayas (10.8), and Central Luzon (10.1), while lower levels were seen in Cagayan Valley (4.1), Central Visayas (4.8), and NIR (5.2)."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Socioeconomic patterns are mixed, with broad declines from 2022",
        "body": "Urban and rural levels both declined (10.2 to 8.6 urban; 9.4 to 7.5 rural). By wealth, the 2025 range is relatively narrow (7.0 to 9.2). Education does not follow a single linear pattern: post-secondary is highest (13.9), while Grades 11-12 is lower (3.4), and several education groups declined from 2022."
      }
    ],
    "takeaways": [
      "Traditional contraceptive use among all women declined between 2022 and 2025 at the national level and across many subgroups.",
      "Use remains concentrated among older women and women with children, and stays very low among teenagers and women with no children.",
      "Regional variation is still wide, so national averages alone can hide large local differences."
    ]
  },
